item.title: All Mixed Up
item.description:
• Read Papers
  • Post

Read Papers

First go ahead and download all of the papers before going through the list

Week 11 materials

Now below is a list of papers assigned for this week. While you must read those under Required, consider giving the ones under Optional a go.

Title Citation Optional Required
Developing Good Research Questions Bufkin (2007)
Toward a conceptual framework for mixed-method evaluation designs Greene, Caracelli, & Graham (1989)
Mixed Methods Research Designs in Counseling Psychology Hanson (2005)
The Meanings of Self-Ratings of Health: A Qualitative and Quantitative Approach Idler (1999)
Crossing Anxious Borders: Teaching Across the Quantitative–Qualitative ‘Divide’ Luttrell (2005)
Paradigms Lost and Pragmatism Regained Morgan (2006)
Strategies for ensuring trustworthiness in qualitative research projects Shenton (2004)
Depression and Substance Use in Two Divergent High School Cultures: A Quantitative and Qualitative Analysis Way, Stauber, Nakkula, & London (1994)

Post

  1. Read and write a single post under #mixed-methods that compares, contrasts, and synthesizes:
    1. Greene, Caracelli, & Graham (1989),
    2. Hanson (2005), and
    3. Idler (1999) Then discuss which you found to be the most interesting and why. If you did not find any to be of interest, please state your reason.

  2. Read Shenton (2004) and write a single post under #trustworthiness that address the following
    • if you identify mostly or fully with quantitative methodological approaches:
      1. State this in your title somewhere.
      2. Discuss your agreement or disagreement of Shenton’s argument. Please be thorough and justify.
      3. Ask a question about the reading that you believe a qualitative person should be able to answer.
    • if you identify mostly or fully with qualitative methodological approaches:
      1. State this in your title somewhere.
      2. Discuss your agreement or disagreement of Shenton’s argument. Please be thorough and justify.
      3. Ask a question about the reading that you believe a quantitative person should be able to answer.

Respond to Posts

  2. Within #including-kec-parts if

  • if you identified mostly or fully with quantitative methodological approaches in Week 11, then locate a person who identifies as qualitative and answer their question to the best of your ability.

  • if you identified mostly or fully with qualitative methodological approaches in Week 11, then locate a person who identifies as quantitative and answer their question to the best of your ability.

item.title: Rethinking the Way You Think
item.description:
• Read Some Papers
    • Note about the posts

Read Some Papers

For each reading below, write a single post on Slack with the following:

  • a reflection / reaction to the content and
  • a question about something specific
Reading Channel
Davidson, J. (2007). Editorial: Unlearning some of our social scientist habits. Journal of MultiDisciplinary Evaluation 4(8). 3-6. #davidson
Mathison, S. (2006). What is the difference between evaluation and research - and why do we care? In N.L. Smith and P.R. Brandon (Eds.) Fundamental issues in evaluation. Guilford Press. #mathison

Note about the posts

Remember this is a graduate level class and your writing should reflect that. Moreover, these postings should be in APA 7th Edition formatting unless otherwise noted. The following general idea will be used when assessing your initial posts, but this is not a rubric.

Marker Point Value Criteria
11.5

Posts are well defined that fully address and develop all aspects of the prompt such that they

advance the discussion,
are factually correct,
are cited correctly when necessary, and
provide a clear, concise, reflective and substantive contribution
10

Posts are mostly well defined that tend to address all aspects of the prompt such that they

generally advance the discussion,
are factually correct,
are cited correctly when applicable, but
lack clarity or full development of the concept(s)
5

Posts are undertsandable but are not cohesive such that they do lack

clarity or
depth or
non-repetitiveness or
preparedness or
justification
0

Posts are generally incoherant or superficial such that they are

repeated or
incorrect or
irrelevant or
off-topic
0 Posts are nonexistent or lack merit

item.title: Who's Values Are Valuable?
item.description:
• Read the Book
  • Read a Paper
  • Respond to Posts
    • Note about the responding to posts

Read the Book

Please read and address the following questions using a single post

Title Chapter Question Channel
“Values” in Evaluation 6 Say you are an evaluator in a scenario where there are multiple sponsors all of equal importance. Each sponsor wants you to evaluate something specific but all of the evaluands are mutually exclusive and independent. With a limited timeframe, you cannot possibly study everything all of the stakeholders want. How do you prioritize what gets sone while still being able to develop a case that your evaluation was valuable? #which-values

Read a Paper

Title Chapter Question Channel
Valuing, Evaluation Methods, and the Politicization of the Evaluation Process Chelimsky (2012) Assume that there is some level of politicization of the evaluative process in government. How egregious do you think this is? Provide some evidence in your narrative regarding specific programs and how you currently see/ have seen this politicization in action. #evaluation-politicization
